=== Neighborhood systems ===
Intuitively, convergence of a net formula_280 means that the values formula_182 come and stay as close as we want to formula_81 for large enough formula_206 Given a point formula_81 in a topological space, let formula_385 denote the set of all neighbourhoods containing formula_56 Then formula_385 is a directed set, where the direction is given by reverse inclusion, so that formula_388 if and only if formula_23 is contained in formula_390 For formula_391 let formula_392 be a point in formula_124 Then formula_394 is a net. As formula_23 increases with respect to formula_396 the points formula_392 in the net are constrained to lie in decreasing neighbourhoods of formula_32. Therefore, in this neighborhood system of a point formula_81, formula_392 does indeed converge to formula_81 according to the definition of net convergence.

Given a subbase formula_402 for the topology on formula_12 (where note that every base for a topology is also a subbase) and given a point formula_95 a net formula_29 in formula_12 converges to formula_81 if and only if it is eventually in every neighborhood formula_408 of formula_56 This characterization extends to neighborhood subbases (and so also neighborhood bases) of the given point formula_56

===Limits in a Cartesian product===

A net in the product space has a limit if and only if each projection has a limit.

Explicitly, let formula_411 be topological spaces, endow their Cartesian product 
